{
  "text": "The Fisher kernel [CITATION_1] denotes a general class of generative kernels that can be derived out of any parametric generative model. The underlying idea of the approach is to represent an input sample x in a feature space defined by the derivative of the log-likelihood log P(x|θ) of the generative model, with respect to its parameters θ . The Fisher kernel has been introduced in [CITATION_2] with application to sequential data classification, using the hidden Markov model (HMM) as generative model for sequences. In [CITATION_3] , it has been extended to deal with treestructured data using the standard HTMM [CITATION_4] as a generative model for the structured samples. Note that the Fisher tree kernel is not convolutional, since the matching between two trees is performed based on the similarity between the respective Fisher scores, which does not allow direct matching between substructures. The computational complexity of the Fisher kernel depends on the parameterization of the underlying generative model. In [CITATION_5] , it has been discussed an alternative feature space obtained by concatenating the sufficient HTMM statistics, as well as a tree kernel based on the probability product approach in [CITATION_6] . A comparative analysis in [CITATION_7] shows that the Fisher Kernel has the best performance among the three in tree classification tasks and is therefore used as a baseline in the experimental assessment in Section IV.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "14336127",
    "[CITATION_2]": "14336127",
    "[CITATION_3]": "12919880",
    "[CITATION_4]": "9651365",
    "[CITATION_5]": "6786332",
